In the end, Pita is freed and Creasy dies, more rubble than man. Had the late Tony Scott realized what a cottage industry revenge pictures would soon be, Creasy would probably be with us now, applying his particular set of skills to untold sequels. Jason Concepcion
shows.title: Man on Fire

shows.writeup: Despite the genuine novelty of its representation in the context of American television, Ramy fits into a recognizable template. Like Seinfeld before it, Ramy is named after and led by a performer who pulls inspiration from his own life. Like Louie, Ramy augments the model with highbrow touches: bisexual lighting, moments of surrealism, naturalistic staging. Ramy is produced by the television department of the widely admired film studio A24; its writers room includes Sundance darling Minhal Baig and Transparent alumna Bridget Bedard. Theres no shortage of easy comparisons across a television landscape thats found individual perspectives a worthwhileand replicableinvestment. Alison Herman
shows.title: Ramy

shows.writeup: The Gossip Girl revival, it turns out, does make a compelling case for itself. That doesnt mean its without major flawsonly that it fulfills the sine qua non of the modern revival: some sort of purpose besides cynically recycling IP. Gossip Girl first aired on the CW, and before the pandemic prolonged production and delayed its release, showrunner Joshua Safrans reimagining was planned as a star attraction for the newly launched HBO Max. Now, Gossip Girl is still a high-budget tentpole, stuffed with celebrity cameos (Princess Nokia) and glossy locations (a 15th birthday party held at the famed Webster Hall). Its also a sincerely novel take on the source material. Alison Herman
shows.title: Gossip Girl

shows.writeup: LeBron, D-Wade, Melo, and the U.S. squad that reclaimed dominance in international basketball recount their journey in this fizzy and entertaining doc.
shows.title: The Redeem Team
Dunkirk
shows.writeup:
When bombs drop in Dunkirk, every man in sight falls to take cover. They fall by the thousands: a cascade of cowering, vulnerable soldiers with nothing to hide beneath save their helmets, beach brush, and occasional debris. None of that saves them. Completely exposed to German attack, these British and French soldiers, numbering more than 300,000, are waiting for evacuation from the beaches of Dunkirk, France, where their army has been forcefully separated from their allies, making them susceptible to a devastating massacrea massacre that would win Germany the war. The year is 1940: The stakes couldnt be higher. After the bombs hit and the air clears, the men who survive get back up to keep waiting, watching as the Royal Navy vessels sent to save them get downed, again and again, by German planes. The rest of the men dont get up. K. Austin Collins

Dunkirk is leaving HBO Max on Nov. 11.

Thrashing alongside these ideas of cultural expansion is a fight to protect the home country from a war-profiteering thief named Ulysses Klaue (Andy Serkis, having an enormous amount of fun) and his partner, the American radical Erik Killmonger (Michael B. Jordan). In the third Captain America movie, Civil War, and the second Avengers movie, Age of Ultron, were confronted with the cost of war, and what it means to be a patriot, whether in the United States or the fictionalized Eastern European nation of Sokovia. In Black Panther, the incursion of dangerous new forces incites tribal warfarethe Wakandan people turned against one another, small differences rupturing a nation. The shades of a different, very real kind of civil war ripple through these scenes, whether recalling Rwanda, Darfur, or the United States. Black Panther is often a joyful exploration of culture, love, and tradition. Its also a war movie. Sean Fennessey
shows.title: Black Panther
Pineapple Express
shows.writeup: The year is 2008. Twelve months removed from the undeniable hits of Superbad and Knocked Up, Seth Rogen and super-producer Judd Apatow have returned to take over yet another summer. Their secret weapon? A joint in the shape of a crucifix. Pineapple Express marked a moment in time when Rogen, Apatow, et al. could do no wrong; when they took their clout (and subsequently high budgets) as hitmakers and made an actual blockbuster comedy. The movie has the fast-paced dialogue of Superbad and the stoner jokes of Knocked Up, but it also has gigantic explosions, car chases, and gun fights. It also has Rogen at his best, James Franco at his most likable, and Danny McBride delivering a heat-check performance to end all heat-check performances. In 2008, there was nothing better than seeing this movie in a theater. In 2022, the feeling can almost be replicated via streaming. Andrew Gruttadaro

Scott Derricksons long-delayed horror followup to 2010s Sinister is a coming-of-age movie in ghoulish attire. One part Dazed and Confused, one part Salems Lot, and not so much scary as magically disturbing.
shows.title: The Black Phone

shows.writeup: Now that Morbius has been released, our worst fears have been realized. Sony has distributed a film that is so breathtakingly terrible, and so excruciating to watch, that it could be mistaken for one of the 10 plagues of Egypt. I truly believe that Morbiuss opening weekend is the three days of darkness foretold in the Bible. Our only recourse is to drive a proverbial stake through the heart of this Marvel legend and ensure that a sequel never sees the light of day. Miles Surrey
shows.title: Morbius
Interview With the Vampire
shows.writeup: When you hear Interview With the Vampire, youre probably reminded of the 1994 movie that featured Tom Cruise and Brad Pitt at the absolute peaks of their hair journeys. AMC has resurrected Anne Rices gothic opus for TV, and while it doesnt have the follicular fortitude of the 90s film, it does feature an exciting cast of mostly up-and-comersand really good reviews. The story and setting is pretty much the same, but creator Rolin Jones (formerly a writer on shows such as Friday Night Lights and Boardwalk Empire) has updated the story for 2022 and injected a curious spark of humor that prevents things from growing too languid episode-to-episode. Vampires abound in modern pop culture, but these ones can stay. Andrew Gruttadaro
If You Can Watch Only One Season: Season 3. Two words: Scary. Island.
shows.title: The Real Housewives of New York City

shows.writeup: We Own This City is the most pedigreed miniseries to be released in 2022: coming from HBO, it was produced by The Wire veterans David Simon and George Pelecanos; based on a book by award-winning journalist Justin Fenton about the corruption within the Baltimore Police Departments Gun Trace Task Force; directed by Reinaldo Marcus Green, who helmed the Academy Awardwinning King Richard; starring Jon Bernthal, Josh Charles, Wunmi Mosaku, and more. All of that comes together to make an urgent, arresting TV show that echoes the greatness of HBO in the early 2000s. Andrew Gruttadaro
shows.title: We Own This City
Sideways
shows.writeup: Also known as The Movie That Taught America What Pinot Noir Is, Sideways was the award season surprise of 2005. It follows Paul Giamatti and Thomas Haden Church as they traipse through the Napa Valley, swilling luxurious vintages, tanking the value of merlot, and chasing love and lust. Giamatti plays the neurotic oenophile Miles Raymond, while Haden Church plays his much more self-assured friend Jack Cole. Miles wants to drown in a wine glass; Jack wants one more sexual conquest before getting married. Thats where Sandra Oh and Virginia Madsen come in, and when this delightful little comedy gets legs. Andrew Gruttadaro

shows.title: Big
shows.writeup: Some funny things happen in Big, and then more funny things happen, and then 35 minutes later Tom Hankss character is working as the vice president in charge of production at a toy company and living in what appears to be a multimillion-dollar corner apartment in New York. He goes on a couple of adventures, has sex with an adult woman (!!!), wears a tuxedo with sparkles on it, plays a gigantic keyboard with his feet, and generally enjoys his new life its a fun movie and a silly movie and a lighthearted movie. Except heres the thing: Its super not any of those things. Its the reverse of all those things. The only way it works as those things is if you look at it through Joshs eyes, which is what youre supposed to do because Josh is the centerpiece. But by any other measure and from the perspective of any of the other characters in Big, it is a horrifying movie. Shea Serrano

Created by New Girls Liz Meriwether, bankrolled by Hulu, and centered on a jaw-dropping lead performance by Amanda Seyfried, The Dropout actually adds something substantive to the oceans of ink already spilled about Elizabeth Holmes and Theranos, the company she co-led with longtime boyfriend Sunny Balwani. Holmes herself is a black hole, with everything from her voice to her miraculous blood-testing device an empty affectation. Meriwether and Seyfried craft a convincing portrait of Holmes as a woman of genuine trauma, crushing insecurity, and utterly bizarre dance routines. But they never let her or her highest-profile marks, like executives at Walgreens or former Secretary of State George Shultz, off the hookif anything, they make Holmes more terrifying in psychological context, not less. Seyfried won an Emmy for the performance, and for good reason. Alison Herman
shows.title: The Dropout
I Am Legend
shows.writeup: Will Smiths peak, as a steely everyman sprinting either toward or away from grave danger, is 2007s I Am Legend. The shaky, dimly lit claustrophobia of this scene has stayed with me, the rare instance when he let his charisma fully dissolve into actual terror. Of course, in I Am Legend, he also mostly banters with a dog. Rob Harvilla

shows.title: Keeping Up With the Kardashians
shows.writeup: When Kristen Mary Jenner was still a relatively unknown mother of six with a thing for sweat suits, she met with American Idol host Ryan Seacrest to pitch a show about her family. Since the 1980s, her manicured brood had picked up celebrity connections like Malibu metal detectorists do lost jewelry. Her late ex-husband, Robert Kardashian, was a well-connected defense lawyer whod been part of one of the most-watched trials in the U.S. Her new husband was an Olympic gold medalistcumWheaties box ambassador. Her daughters from her first marriage had grown up alongside celebrity kids like Nicole Richie. And her daughter Kim was a tabloid accessory to it girl Paris Hilton and the star of a recently leaked sex tape with the R&B artist Ray J. At the time, Seacrests production company was in its infancy, and he thought a family-oriented reality show in the mold of The Osbournes could be promising. Well never know what exactly Kris said that day, but it was her chance to make the case that she and her kin were not just footnotes in tabloid captions, but compelling personalities in their own right. Neither she nor Seacrest couldve predicted at that 2007 meeting that, over the next decade, the Kardashian-Jenners would reinvent the industry of fame itself. Alyssa Bereznak

On Ozark, the Netflix crime drama that feels like an algorithmic response to the popularity of Breaking Bad, Jason Batemans Marty Byrde began laundering money for a Mexican drug cartel to protect his family. (In fairness to Marty, the only reason he was put in this precarious situation is because his business partner was caught skimming money from the cartel, which wanted to tie up loose ends.) But over the course of four seasons, Martys desperate bid for survival in the Lake of the Ozarks has evolved into an insatiable lust for power thats left a string of bodies in its wake. Marty said it himself in the series premiere: Money is, at its essence, that measure of a mans choices. And those choices paint an ugly portrait of not just Marty, but also of his wife, Wendy (an excellent Laura Linney), whose cutthroat ambition for the family business has led the character to emerge as the shows equivalent to Walter White. Miles Surrey
shows.title: Ozark

shows.writeup: Before Succession, there was Arrested Development. Sure, the Mitchell Hurwitz sitcom from the early 2000s doesnt have the HBO sheen or the fancy theme song, but it does just as good a job of poking fun at the mega-rich and positing that theyre defined not by competency, but by dysfunction. Swap a media empire for a real estate business (and a banana stand); swap Logan Roy for George Bluth Sr.; swap Roman Roys daddy issues for Buster Bluths, uh, pirate hook. Arrested Development is a legendary comedy with a style that isnt easily mimicked, but beyond all the wordplay and pitch-perfect performances from a loaded cast, its a testament to just how fun it is to laugh at a bunch of rich idiots. Andrew Gruttadaro
shows.title: Arrested Development
V/H/S/99
shows.writeup:
Its baaaack. One of the most durable anthology franchises in movie history is back with another installment of spooky stories, including new short films from Johannes Roberts, Vanessa and Joseph Winter, and Flying Lotus.

Streaming now on Shudder.

Calamitously under-marketed, this fresh update of Gregory McDonalds detective-journalist hero (starring a perfect Jon Hamm) nails the source material.

Streaming now on VOD. Arrives on Showtime on October 28.
shows.title: Confess, Fletch

shows.writeup: Barry Jenkinss underseen feature after his Academy Awardwinning Moonlight is one of the more sophisticated young love stories in recent memory, and also an adaptation of a James Baldwin story that some believed could not be adapted. Consider this proving that wrong.
shows.title: If Beale Street Could Talk
The Harry Potter Series
shows.writeup: Consider the opening sequence of Harry Potter and the Philosophers Stone, first revealed to Muggle eyes more than 20 years ago. Harry Potter doesnt speak in the books first chapter; he appears only in its final pages, a sleeping tot with a fresh forehead scar. But the chapter is important, depicting a bifurcated world wed come to adore. Its magical, mentioning brigades of owls and adults in strange cloaks, then showing a professorial Animagus, a flying motorcycle, and a wizard named Albus with a twinkle in his eye. "The Boy Who Lived" starts a lengthy build toward a climax, yielding, eventually, a battle between that boy and the Dark Lord whose soul suffered eight distinct deaths. It suffers from no negatives and contains plenty of delightful details besides, from Dumbledore tucking his beard into his belt to the foreshadowing of Sirius Black. It is, all components considered, exposition nonpareil. Zach Kram

shows.title: Margin Call
shows.writeup: Its 2007. The economy is about to collapse. Whats going on in the heart of Wall Street? J.C. Chandors financial thriller Margin Call is a window into exactly that: taking place over the course of 24 hours at the edge of the 07-08 financial crisis, a group of employees at an unnamed investment bank scramble to react to disastrously high volatility and overleveraged assets. Margin Call is a slice of one of the most important moments in recent American history. But beyond that? Its also just a really good, well-crafted flick. Andrew Gruttadaro

Its no surprise that off the back of Drive to Survives success, Netflix and the shows producing team are looking to replicate its buzz with another show highlighting a sport thats ripe for a potential breakout: tennis. The new docuseries Break Point follows key players on the ATP and WTA tours over the course of the 2022 season. It may be too soon to say whether Break Point will grow the global popularity of tennis, but with the show featuring the kind of behind-the-scenes access that became one of Drive to Survives biggest selling points, theres plenty that could reel viewers in. For better or for worse, that includes Break Point bringing attention to its own Aussie athlete as the primary subject of its series premiere: Nick Kyrgios. Miles Surrey
shows.title: Break Point

shows.writeup: If you ever wondered what it would be like if the cast of Laguna Beach grew up and got their real estate licenses, but never stopped swapping spit and stank faces at outlandishly themed parties, then Selling Sunset has the sister show for you. Season 1 of Selling the OC follows the shiny new Orange County division of the Oppenheim Group and its coterie of thirsty real estate agents as they chase beachfront properties in heels as high as their listing prices. Most importantly, Selling the OC is outfitted with not one, not two, but three rivaling Alexandras. Come for the $106 million oceanside mansion with a retractable roof and parking for 25; stick around to figure out what the hell a nosey is; binge the entire eight-episode season in one sitting to find out which Alexandra reigns supreme on Zillow. Jodi Walker
shows.title: Selling the OC
Community
shows.writeup:
Community started out with a premise fit for network TV: A disgraced lawyer (Joel McHale) who has to go to community college to earn a degree invents a study group in order to get closer to a female student (Gillian Jacobs). But the joy of rewatching Community is seeing how that basic setup is quickly warped and twisted beyond recognition. Filtered through the mind of showrunner Dan Harmon, Community became deeply meta, deeply referential, and deeply idiosyncratic. Start off with the normcore pilot episode today and 48 hours later youll be basking in the sublimity of a paintball Western or the darkest timeline. Andrew Gruttadaro

Community is leaving Prime Video on Nov. 7.

shows.title: Severance
shows.writeup: It can be tricky to maintain a healthy work-life balance, so imagine if you could sever your life between what you do in the office and everything outside of it. Thats the setup for the absorbing Apple TV+ drama Severance, which follows a group of workers at the mysterious Lumon Industries who volunteered for the experimental procedure. The concept wouldnt feel out of place on an episode of Black Mirror, and like the popular sci-fi series, Severance excels because its technology feels both plausible and terrifying if it fell in the wrong hands. Miles Surrey

shows.title: Better Call Saul
shows.writeup: That Better Call Saul culminates in such restrained fashion, especially compared to Breaking Bad, speaks to the shows different set of priorities. At its bestso basically, its entire runBetter Call Saul reveled in detail, process, and what made its characters tick. It was a series that honestly felt more at home crafting montages within Albuquerques legal system than diving into the citys well-established criminal underworld. But above everything else, Better Call Saul showed that its never too late to stop breaking bad for the ones you love. Miles Surrey

When Harry Met Sally is the greatest rom-com ever made. Its the product of the galacticos of the cute, talky, adult comedy: Nora Ephron, Rob Reiner, Meg Ryan, Billy Crystal, and Carrie Fisher, all at the peak of their powers. Its set in the perfect place and at the perfect time: a bourgeois corner of New York City in the 1980s, when men wore sweaters and women wore hats. You couldnt ask for better building blocks.

But thats not what makes it great. A majority of romantic comedies set their focus on the beginning of a relationship: the exciting part. The thesis of When Harry Met Sally is that love is not about the spark, but about how you feel years down the line. And somehow, over the course of just 95 minutes, we get to see a relationship develop over the course of 12 years. Even considering that there are basically only four characters in the movie, its an astonishing bit of writing and acting to establish two leads who just get each other so completely. Its the rom-com every filmmaker should aspire to make, and the romance every couple should aspire to have. Michael Baumann
shows.title: When Harry Met Sally

shows.writeup: If You Can Watch Only One Season: Start with Season 2, which sees the addition of a true catalyst, Kathryn Dennis, join as a full-time cast member.
shows.title: Southern Charm
Top Gun: Maverick
shows.writeup: Top Gun: Maverick at first glance seems designed to go further and finally have Tom Cruise embrace his role as elder statesman. After crashing a hypersonic jet in the opening scenes, Maverick gets grounded and reassigned to the flight academy. Its not just a new assignment; for Maverick, its akin to death. The future is coming, his gruff superior tells him. And youre not in it. Technically, hes talking about how drones are making human pilots like Maverick unnecessary, but he might as well be telling Cruise that movie stars arent important in the age of uncanny CGI and franchise hegemony. Not to worry: Over the course of the film, Maverick finds renewed purpose as a mentor to the young pilots, and Cruise wears it well. The character makes amends with Rooster (Miles Teller), Gooses son, who blames Maverick for holding him back in his Navy career. He properly guides the cocky, young Hangman (Glen Powell), who surely reminds Maverick of himself, by keeping him grounded during the final assignment, which puts him in just the right spot to save the day when Maverick and Goose are in danger. The transition from hotshot to aging mentor seems so natural that it actually comes as a surprise when Maverickand Cruisewrestles back the controls at the last minute and spends the last 30 minutes performing the most death-defying stunts of his career. Noah Gittell

Gina Prince-Bythewoods semi-autobiographical film follows Monica Wright (Sanaa Lathan) and Quincy McCall (Omar Epps) as they discover their talents and decipher their complex relationshipswith basketball, with their families, with each other. The story is told through four quarters, following Monica and Q from when they were childhood frenemies (Monica was a Lakers fan, Qs dad played for the Clippers) to their respective paths to high school basketball stardom, college freshman year woes, and dreams of going pro. But these bare bones of the plot dont convey the movies special appeal, Roger Ebert wrote in his review. It is a sports film seen mostly from the womans point of view. And heres the most amazing thing: It considers sports in terms of career, training, motivation and strategy. The big game scenes involve behavior and attitude, not scoring. The movie sees basketball as something the characters do as a skill and a living, not as an excuse for audience-pleasing jump shots at the buzzer. Jordan Ligons
shows.title: Love & Basketball
Survivor: David vs. Goliath
shows.writeup: David vs. Goliath is one of the best new-school seasons of Survivor: the premise is compelling; the players are memorable (from quirky-yet-lovable robotics professor Christian Hubicki to recent Emmy winner Mike White); and the gameplay post-merge is as twisty and inspiring as you could hope for. Youll enjoy both the awkward momentsyou wont get it now, but Natalie, can I have your jacket? Natalie? Natalie? is an all-timeras well as the uplifting ones, which surface in the form of challenge triumphs and odd-couple friendships. (Also streaming on Netflix and Hulu.)

shows.title: Bachelor in Paradise
shows.writeup: The only reason to watch The Bachelor and The Bachelorette is to be familiar with the people going on Bachelor in Paradise. Were only one episode into the new season and theres already drama on the beach between some of the lesser-known cast members of Bachelor Nation, namely (and perhaps fittingly) Romeo (from Michelles season), is-she-really-a-doctor Kira (Claytons season), and proudly weird Jill (Claytons season). In this love triangle alone, the words slut-shaming and gaslighting have been thrown about, and I cannot stress this enough: These are the shows junior varsity players. Amelia Wedemeyer

What else would you expect with Paul Thomas Anderson directing a movie called Boogie Nights? With a title like that, the soundtrack simply had to be good. From the three-plus-minute tracking that opens the movie, the viewer is viscerally transported to the 70s with probably the best use of the Emotions iconic Best of My Love put to film. Marvin Gaye; the Commodores; Electric Light OrchestraBoogie Nights drops classic after classic to infuse its scenes with the mood of 70s disco, dancing, drugs, and beyond. Whats so great about this soundtrack is not simply how infectious the songs are, but also how vital they are to establishing the pace and energy of the movie. The film couldve been average had the music disappointed; its one of PTAs all-time bests because the soundtrack absolutely delivers. Aric Jenkins
shows.title: Boogie Nights

shows.writeup: If your TV tastes skew more toward heartfelt than dramatic, Queer Eye and its mission to better the lives of everyday people is the show for you.
shows.title: Queer Eye

shows.writeup: Its January, which to a certain nation means one thing: the return of the Most Dramatic Series on Television. On January 23, the Bachelor Mansion will once again open its doors to a bevy of marketing managers, nurses, and content creators, and this season theyll compete to win the heart of Zach Shallcross from Season 19 of The Bachelorette. You probably know the rest of the drill here: there will be a villain who steals other girls time with the Bachelor; there will be heart-wrenching stories of trauma revealed on dates that end in fireworks, literal and figurative; there will be accusations of not being there for the Right Reasons. But thats a feature, not a bug: at this point in The Bachelors run, its the familiarity that keeps you coming back. Andrew Gruttadaro
shows.title: The Bachelor

shows.writeup: If You Can Watch Only One Season: It has to be Season 4; the Housewives world is known for throwing dramatic dinner parties, and the one hosted by Candiace Dillard Bassett during Potomacs fourth season could quite possibly be the best.
shows.title: The Real Housewives of Potomac

shows.writeup: No one is doing dystopia quite like the South Koreans, and we are so lucky to be living in a timeline in which we can stream their shows without having to go through the headache of finding a VPN or a sketchy tube site. Singles Inferno, which can be watched with English subtitles or English dubbing, is a combination of Survivor and Bachelor in Paradise, with its contestants being stranded on Inferno, a deserted island where they cant reveal their real ages or professions, must cook for themselves, and compete against each other for dates. If two people decide to couple up, they can escape to Paradise together, where they can ask their partner whatever they want and live in luxury for a night. As is normal for dating shows, the couples find themselves in love triangles and other geometric shapes, all the while a group of four narrators watch and critique the experience. Amelia Wedemeyer
shows.title: Single's Inferno
The Wolf of Wall Street
shows.writeup: The Wolf of Wall Street is about an amoral man (played by Leonardo DiCaprio) who leads a group of equally amoral men as they attempt to make fortunes on Wall Street in the 80s and 90s. As chance would have it, the leader, Jordan Belfort, was a traditionally trained stockbroker, and so he pairs his training with his hard-sell technique (where he basically just bombards clients with words, pummeling and sometimes shaming them into submission) and an illegal penny-stock scheme, then teaches all of his loser friends to do the same. He is a slickster and a swindler and possibly a genius, which I suppose are pretty good traits to have if you are a wolf on Wall Street. Shea Serrano

shows.title: The Punisher
shows.writeup: The Punisher is perhaps Netflixs most unexpected Marvel series. There werent even plans to make The Punisher, but after Frank Castleand more specifically, the excellent, committed actor who played him, Jon Bernthalstole the second season of Daredevil, the streaming service and studio called an audible. But thats not the only reason The Punisher feels surprising: Castle also isnt, lets say, a typical heroif you can even call him one. Traumatized by the death of his family, he becomes an avatar for vengeance with a skull-shaped logo and a penchant for murdering criminals using an absurd arsenal of semi-automatic weapons. To put it another way: If a kid dresses up as Batman or Superman for Halloween, its adorable; if a kid shows up at your door dressed as the Punisher, you should be concerned. Miles Surrey

The Good Fight doesnt feel like it was derailed by the pandemic, or like its suffered from the Kings packed schedule. If anything, the show has hit closer to home than ever. When a renegade judge played by Mandy Patinkinthe platonic ideal of a guest star for showrunners Robert and Michelle Kingstarts his own unauthorized court, it seems oddly rational. In the face of so much uncertainty, all you can do is make your own rules. Alison Herman
shows.title: The Good Fight
10 Things I Hate About You
shows.writeup: Like all adaptations, the teen classic also allows for subversion as well as dutiful translation. 10 Things I Hate About You, in particular, turns its misogynist blueprinttheres a sexist smear in the name!on its head. William Shakespeares Taming of the Shrew has Kat Stratford literally beaten into submission, a disturbing scenario originally played for laughs.10 Things makes Kat slightly insufferable and even calls her out for her self-righteous privilege, but mostly sees her principles and stubbornness as virtues to be rewarded with a partner who sees her for who she is. Alison Herman

For a few years now, its been difficult to watch traditional superhero stories without thinking about The Boys. The Amazon Prime Video series, adapted from a DC-turned-Dynamite comic created by Garth Ennis and Darick Robertson, set out to take the piss out of superheroes and, before its second season, graduated to depicting its headlining supernonhero taking a piss on the public. But something surprising happened to the upstart series between its 2019 premiere and its Season 3 finale: The Boys became a blockbuster brand of its own. Ben Lindbergh
shows.title: The Boys
Orphan: First Kill
shows.writeup: Were not sure who asked for this, but were happy they did. More than 10 years after the deranged original, Esther is back to terrorize her first family.

If You Can Watch Only One Season: Vapid 20-somethings with first-world problems never looked funnier than they do in Season 2 of the RHOBH spinoff, which includes a moment referred to as the Bitch slap heard round the world.
shows.title: Vanderpump Rules

shows.writeup: If it werent for the direct reference to the Avengers during its narrated introduction, it wouldnt be all that easy to tell that Werewolf by Night is the latest entry into the Marvel Cinematic Universe. And thats a great thing: The 54-minute TV special is a delightful homage to the monster movies of the 1930s and 1940s, one fittingly styled in black and white with an admirable commitment to the charming cheesiness of the film era. Starring Gael Garca Bernal in a tale inspired by its namesake comic series, Werewolf by Night is the first entry in Marvel Studios Special Presentationsand it showcases the new collection of TV specials as a potential space for filmmakers to get a little weird and flex some extra creative freedom. Helmed by the Oscar-winning composer Michael Giacchino, the special hasunsurprisinglya wonderful score that sets the spooky tone as the multihyphenate pulls double duty. (This is the guy who composed the music for the saddest Pixar scene ever, after all.) It might not be the scariest flick youll see this time of the year, but Werewolf by Night is surprisingly gory by Marvel standards, and serves as a fun hour of TV fit for the Halloween season. Daniel Chin
shows.title: Werewolf by Night
Fast & Furious 6
shows.writeup: Heres everything Fast & Furious 6 has going for it: Letty comes back from the dead; its revealed that Letty didnt actually die all of her memories were merely erased; Letty and MMA star Gina Carano get into an all-out, brutal fist fight in the London Underground; after being enemies in Fast Five, the Rock becomes part of the crew in Fast & Furious 6, solidifying Dom and Hobbs as the beefiest tag team duo in action movie history; this Vin Diesel stunt; this Vin Diesel stunt; this Vin Dieselthe Rock move; a climax that includes Dom driving a car through the belly of an exploding airplane; and of course, the mid-credits scene in which Jason Statham is introduced to the series and its revealed that his character, Deckard Shaw, brother to Furious 6 villain Owen Shaw, was the one who killed Han in Tokyo Drift. If it seems like Fast & Furious 6 checks all of our boxes, we should probably say that it absolutely does. Andrew Gruttadaro

The movie didnt truly become a curiosity until teenagers who missed it in theaters began finding it. The film had three sharp hooks: a deep cast of angsty up-and-comers, a new-wave soundtrack, and a Reagan-era setting. But what really turned Donnie Darko into an obsession was its complex yet accessible plot and themes, which kept college kids up at night, debating in smoke-filled dorm rooms. What is life? What does it all mean? Like The Matrix did a few years prior, the eerie indie challenged an audience weaned on meta slasher flicks and raunchy comedies. And while its profundity decreases the older you get, Donnie Darko will always be a wormhole that sucks in curious adolescents and blows their minds. Alan Siegel
shows.title: Donnie Darko
She-Hulk: Attorney at Law
shows.writeup: Reading comics from the 80s was like reading a novelmany of those bubbles are densely packed with chunks of powerful prose full of threats of bodily harm and to the world at large. With its fierce feminist lead and finger on the pulse of pop culture, She-Hulk proves that modern Marvel series are evolving in the same way. That also means that theres room to play. As with the 2014 She-Hulk comic book series, She-Hulk the show appears to be more of a vehicle to tell the smaller tales that help turn the larger MCU weve seen in the films and series released thus far into a more fully realized universe. Its cameo-driven stories could become that weeks memeas Jen Walters puts it in an upcoming episode, Its like giving the show Twitter armor for a weekand could even serve as mini-pilots for future adventures in the Marvel Cinematic Universe. She-Hulk could be the prototype for a live-action What If?style show, where the aim isnt necessarily a new addition to the main plot, but an opportunity to see the MCU from multiple perspectives. Khal Davenport

shows.title: Industry
shows.writeup: Wound up with stress and let loose on the trading floor, the neophytes bounce off of one another like caffeinated pinballs. Dissatisfied with her boyfriend and disempowered at work, Yasmin indulges in a kinky flirtation with a smitten colleague. Gus enters a same-sex affair with a straight-presenting superior. Drugs are the offices lifeblood, powering employees through 16-hour days and ensuring they dont waste the remaining eight on wasteful luxuries like sleep. Industrys characters talk like extras from Billions, hyping up shorts and speaking in acronyms like RiF (pronounced riff) or FX (foreign exchange). But in their after-hours exploits, they act like the newest generation of Skinsor Euphoria. Alison Herman
A more intimate follow-up to French filmmaker Celine Sciamma's titanic romance Portrait of a Lady on Fire, Petite Maman is a brief but gorgeous story about childhood and motherhood.
shows.title: Petite Maman
Unforgiven
shows.writeup: Unforgiven remains a masterpiece. It was the first of Clint Eastwoods films to win the Oscar for Best Picture, in 1993. The best lines (I guess you think Im kicking you, Bob) still sing, the seething sense of vengeance is still thrilling, and the thunderclaps still ring out with moral terror. This is a movie about what might happen when, in the dying light of a fading Old West, a cowboy is made to feel like less of a man. K. Austin Collins

shows.title: Iron Man 3
shows.writeup: The one where all the Iron Mans fight each other, this movie also establishes the MCUs Third Movie Rule, which holds as follows: the third movie in a series (Iron Man, Thor, Captain America) will always be better than the second movie in the series. This usually has more to do with the poor quality of the second film than the remarkable quality of the third, but lets go with it. Amanda Dobbins

shows.title: The Great British Baking Show
shows.writeup: About once a year since 2010, 12 people make a momentous pilgrimage. These 12 people are amateur bakersnon-professionals from across the United Kingdom of varying occupation, age, and amounts of mirthand their destination is a charming, oven-filled tent somewhere in the English countryside. Once there, they make epically conceived breads, biscuits the colors of the rainbow, cakes in the shape of human heads, and tarts that hopefully elude sogginess. But mostly, they collectively proceed to burrow their way into our hearts. Andrew Gruttadaro

MacGruber is a silly, violent, sex-filled, SNL sketchbased farce about a truly deplorable man. Aside from his celery-related antics, in the movies 90-minute running time he accidentally blows up his entire team of mercenaries, torches the car of a man who makes fun of his Mazda Miata, and has sex with the ghost of his dead wife in a cemetery. If that doesnt sound like the formula for a Waynes Worldstyle smash hit, thats because its not. Perhaps fittingly, MacGrubers comically inept hero couldnt save it from bombing. After making only $4 million during its opening weekend, the movie grossed a total of $9.3 million. But after quickly fleeing from theaters in the spring of 2010, its become an ass-kickin, throat-rippin cult favorite. Alan Siegel
shows.title: MacGruber

shows.writeup: Den of Thieves is a heist movie. It stars Gerard Butler as Big Nick OBrien, a (probably) crooked law enforcement officer who runs a major crimes unit. And it stars Pablo Schreiber as Ray Merrimen, a former Marine turned bank robber mastermind. And it stars 50 Cent as Levi Enson Levoux, also a former Marine and second-in-command to Merrimen in the heist crew. And it stars OShea Jackson Jr. as Donnie Wilson, a jelly-bellied getaway driver who gets pulled into a job bigger than he can handle (we find out later that actually hes the most devious of the bunch). Merrimen and his team angle to steal $30 million from the Los Angeles Federal Reserve. (To be specific, they hope to steal $30 million that the Federal Reserve is planning to shred, because if they steal that money then theyll be able to spend it freely since nobody will look for it because its supposed to be shredded anyway.) Big Nick and his team angle to stop them. Sometimes its just that simple. Shea Serrano
shows.title: Den of Thieves

shows.writeup: The Walking Deads pilot was filmed in a grainy 16mm that would make the late George A. Romero proud; the first seasons showrunner was Frank Darabont, the man responsible for critically acclaimed dramas like The Shawshank Redemption and The Green Mile; the fate of any character not named Rick Grimes was totally up in the air; and it delivered six mostly compelling installments of TV that considered the philosophical and moral costs of survival. AMC, home of Mad Men and Breaking Bad, had another big hit on its hands, a show that was somehow twisting the pulpy zombie genre into prestige TV. Miles Surrey
shows.title: The Walking Dead

shows.writeup: The Bear knows what it is. That shouldnt be enough to laud a show as one of the years best in our current content Ragnark, but the bar is so low it belongs in the basement. Instead of 60 minutes of prestige TV padding, The Bear settles and thrives within the 30-minute format. Rather than clich jokes about chefs spitting in food, The Bear finds its humor in the much more fraught terrain of interpersonal trauma. Every member of the cast, whether its with the simmering misery of Jeremy Allen Whites Carmy or the abrasive charisma of Ebon Moss-Bachrachs Richie, does just enough to shine without distracting from the ensemble. Any time The Bear is on the edge of making the easier, more expected decision, it veers into something more interestingeven if its imperfect. Charles Holmes
shows.title: The Bear
Bardo, False Chronicle of a Handful of Truths
shows.writeup: Bardo is the Buddhist term for the liminal state between death and rebirthjust in case you were wondering, or wanted to know what to expect before heading into the latest, semi-autobiographical film from legendary Mexican director Alejandro G. Irritu. On the surface, the movie is about a documentarian navigating his worldly success and domestic anxiety. But, of course, theres more to it than that, as Bardo finds itself exploring the boundaries between life and death, dreams and reality, fact and fiction, and Mexico and the United States. Irritu has always pushed boundaries and questioned what it means to create while creating; his latest for Netflix may not be earning the same acclaim as Birdman or The Revenant, but its certainly no departure. Andrew Gruttadaro

Ford v Ferrari features many of the qualitiesa historical basis, fast cars, male friendships, male rivalries, men not wanting to talk openly about their feelings, loud and adrenaline-fueled racing sequencesthat are staples of whats become one of my favorite genres: Dad Cinema. Ford v Ferrari is such a model example of this type of project that I expect test-screening attendees were composed of dads, as assembled by an exalted Committee of Dads, so that the movie could achieve its maximum dad-nesswhich it did. Miles Surrey
shows.title: Ford v Ferrari

shows.writeup: A powerful documentary from director Margaret Brown that tracks the descendants of the survivors of the Clotilda, the last known ship that carried enslaved Africans to the U.S.
shows.title: Descendant
WeCrashed
shows.writeup: Nothing already published about WeWork dug into what we saw as the heart of the story, says Drew Crevello, who cocreated WeCrashed with The Office executive producer Lee Eisenberg. There is no WeWork without Rebekah Neumann, and there is no WeWork without the very specific alchemy of these two personalities coming together. Both Adam and Rebekah Neumann are presented as comedic characters, but its Rebekah who carries the emotional weight. Some pleas for our sympathy are more effective than others. Alison Herman

shows.title: Hard Knocks
shows.writeup: Twenty-one years after its premiere, Hard Knocks continues to be one of HBOs most impressive feats, and though the production value has increased tenfold, the inherently dramatic concept has remained the same (and even spawned an in-season spinoff), drawing new and casual fans to Americas most popular sport. Who knew what it would become? says current NFL Films senior coordinating producer Ken Rodgers. Jake Kring-Schreifels

shows.title: The Rehearsal
shows.writeup: The Rehearsal, a six-episode series, is the second product of an overall deal between Nathan Fielder and HBO, but the first in which Fielder appears in front of the camera. (Fielder is an executive producer on How to With John Wilson, the quirky, digressive docuseries that gives a softer edge to gonzo gimmickry.) The show is, in essence, a supersized version of Nathan for Yous Finding Frances dry run. In an effort to reduce the uncertainty of everyday life, Fielder has volunteers rehearse fraught interactions, from confessing a secret to confronting a sibling. Inevitably, Fielder finds himself drawn into the experiment as more than a neutral observer. Alison Herman

If there's one thing Darren Star knows how to do, it's write compulsively watchable antiheroines in over-the-top outfits. The creator of Sex and the City's Carrie Bradshaw and Younger's Liza Miller, Star then blessed us with Emily Cooper, the namesake of Emily in Paris. (It's supposed to rhyme.) Emily is Carrie if she grew up post-recession and went to a Big Ten school: practical, Midwestern, and chronically basic. When Emily's marketing job takes her to Paris, we get a culture clash comedy that's only partly aware of how insufferable she is. No one thinks Emily in Paris is a great show, but everyone seems to agree it's freakishly compelling. Whether you're bingeing ironically or not, it makes no difference to Netflix's bottom line. Alison Herman
shows.title: Emily in Paris

shows.image: https://storage.googleapis.com/streamingguide-theringer-com-cms/public/media/ringerstreaming/shows/All Quiet On the Western Front_Reiner Bajo (1).jpg
shows.title: All Quiet on the Western Front
shows.writeup: Maybe you remember it as the book every European history professor ever assigned in class. It was also an efficiently adapted epic that won Best Picture in 1930. Now its been adapted once more, putting a hefty budget from Netflix to work in a film that earns its right to stand alongside its source material. Directed by Edward Berger, the story doesnt stray far from Erich Maria Remarques original text, choosing instead to drill deeper into it. The movies been called dextrous and stunning, but also brutal and harrowing. It might not be an easy watchwhich might be why youve heard so little about it since its October releasebut its undoubtedly a rewarding one. Andrew Gruttadaro

shows.title: The Real Housewives of New Jersey
shows.writeup: If You Can Watch Only One Season: Watch Season 1 for everything leading up to Teresa Giudices explosive table flip. Legendary stuff.

Its one of the greatest sports movies ever made. A very bad hockey player (played by Adam Sandler at the height of his powers in the 90s) finds out hes a very good golfer, and is convinced to switch sportsby a former golfer cut down in his prime when an alligator bit his hand offin order to dig his grandmother out of debt. There are too many glorious moments in Happy Gilmore to recount here, from Happys profane disruption of the stuck-up golf world to Christopher McDonalds turn as the genuinely iconic villain Shooter McGavin. You can probably already recite the entire movie from memory, so fire it up and find your happy place once again. Andrew Gruttadaro
shows.title: Happy Gilmore

shows.writeup: Its a great irony of Succession that the plot is set in motion by an insistence on standing still. If Logan Roy had simply celebrated his 80th birthday, handed the keys to Kendall, and moved on to retirement, the show couldve ended with the pilot. Instead, the patriarch refused to budge, a stubborn opposition to substantive change that set off a series worth of schemes, betrayals, and shifting alliances. Alison Herman
shows.title: Succession
Time for Him to Come Home for Christmas

shows.writeup: Jake Gyllenhaal is now known for his deep physical commitment to his roleslosing and gaining weight, exposing himself to harsh mental and physical conditions, and so on. I learned that preparation was my savior, he told EW. Freedom was on the other side of discipline. It was his idea to make the ambulance-chasing crime videographer Lou, in Nightcrawler, creepily gaunt. I would try to eat as few calories as possible, he has said. I knew if I was hungry that I was in the right spot. Physically, it showed itself, but chemically and mentally, I think it was even a more fascinating journey. K. Austin Collins
shows.title: Nightcrawler

shows.writeup: David Lowerys A Ghost Story was intimately metaphysical, shrinking the universe to the size of a deserted, increasingly dilapidated house where a lonely phantom watched as time passed him by. It played an existential melody in a minor key. Working here on a larger canvas and backed by the market-savvy brain trust at A24, the director stands on the shoulders of filmmaking giantsmostly John Boorman of Excaliburwhile grasping for a vanished, mythic grandeur that has as much to do with the New Hollywood of the 1970s as the Round Table. The mission: to imbue sword-and-sorcery cinema with power and glory once more. Adam Nayman
shows.title: The Green Knight
Survivor: Pearl Islands
shows.writeup: A classic early season that brought together some of Survivors most beloved and hated contestantsnamely, Sandra Diaz-Twine, Rupert Boneham, and Jonny Fairplay (Ill let you decide who falls into which category). Pearl Islands might be best known for the dead grandma lie, which, despite it being one of the most iconic moments in reality TV history, really overshadows a season filled with many more memorable moments.

shows.title: The Falcon and the Winter Soldier
shows.writeup: The 2021 Disney+ series doesnt feature the Black Panther, but it does feature members of the Dora Milaje, the elite all-female group of warriors who serve as his protectors. In the miniseries, their members are further explored as they once again cross paths with Bucky Barnes, who they prefer to call the White Wolf.

Whether you have a bunch of tattoos or none at all, you will be quickly absorbed by Ink Master, a competition series thats both a feat of artistry as well as a cutthroat tournament hosted by Dave Navarro (and Joel Madden in the latest season). With 14 seasons featuring what the show hypes as some of the best tattooers from around the country, youll catch on to various tattoo terms and styles as each episode explores different aspects of tattooing (precision, finesse, ingenuity) and style (neo-traditional, new school, black and gray). Ink Master has a notable edge to it, and any show thats been on as long as this one is bound to have early episodes that feel behind the times, but as a window into an under-explored subculture, it delivers. Amelia Wedemeyer
shows.title: Ink Master

shows.writeup: It might be hard to find a dating show on Netflix that doesnt involve wannabe influencers with a penchant for drama, but Love on the Spectrum is that diamond in the rough. The show follows a group of individuals on the autism spectrum and documents their experiences in dating and forming relationships, doing so in a manner that isnt exploitive, but genuine and moving. Be prepared: You WILL become invested in the cast. Amelia Wedemeyer
shows.title: Love on the Spectrum
The Challenge: USA
shows.writeup: Watch as your favorite reality stars across CBS series (namely, Survivor, Big Brother, Love Island USA, and The Amazing Race) try their hand at MTVs iconic reality competition.

shows.title: Survivor: Cagayan
shows.writeup: Hailed as one of the best new-school seasons of Survivor, Cagayan features many of the characteristics the latter years are known for: fast gameplay, random idols, and building a rsum to impress the jury. This time around, castaways are divided into three tribes based on clearly superficial qualitiesthankfully, those labels are essentially thrown out the window and not really brought up again. Instead, were left with a cast of truly chaotic characters fighting one another for $1 million and the title of Sole Survivor. (Also streaming on Hulu.)

shows.title: Honk for Jesus. Save Your Soul.
shows.writeup: Regina Hall and Sterling K. Brown rap along to Crime Mobs Knuck If You Buck in this film. Need I say more?

Paul T. Goldman director Jason Woliner has worked with Sacha Baron Cohen and Nathan Fielder in the past, helming Borat Subsequent Moviefilm and episodes of Nathan for You. That CV is an accurate preview of the Peacock miniseries, which blurs the line between fact and fiction as thoroughly as Woliner's onetime collaborators. The namesake of Paul T. Goldman is a literal Florida Man who claims to have uncovered all kinds of illegal activity through an ugly divorce with his ex-wife. Goldman has already written a book and a screenplay telling his side of the story, but Woliner allows him to direct and star in a dramatic reenactment. Like Fielder's The Rehearsal, Paul T. Goldman brings up ethical quandaries at its own expense; the more we learn about Paul, the less advisable it seems to hand him a large-scale platform, even one that highlights his flaws. But the series six episodes still make for a riveting watchso long as you can handle the discomfort. Alison Herman
shows.title: Paul T. Goldman

shows.writeup:
Promising Young Woman is a visual feast that clashes (in a good way) with the harsh realities of being a woman. Every woman knows a nice guy who at some point revealed himself to not be so nice; a guy who they idealized the way we idealize Seth Cohen, Schmidt, Bash, and the sensitive director of Eighth Grade. These are the nice guys who are our friends, our partners, our family, our coworkers: the kind of men who we think we know until the moment we dont. The kind of men in Promising Young Woman. Carrie Wittmer

Promising Young Woman is leaving HBO Max on Nov. 30.
shows.title: Promising Young Woman
Monster: The Jeffrey Dahmer Story
shows.writeup: For perhaps the first time since The Ringers Streaming Guide was launched in late August, we have encountered a TV show that tests the entire point of this Weekly Top 10. Dahmer is, at worst, not a good show, and at best its a misguided, exploitative one. The series retreads the oft-told story of one of the most infamous serial killers in America, leans into its cocreator Ryan Murphys worst tendencies, and in many ways glorifies a man who murdered 17 men, the majority of whom were gay. (As happened the last time Netflix released content on a notorious serial killer, this series has led to a disconcerting amount of people expressing their attraction to Dahmer on social media.) But Dahmer was also watched for 196.2 million hours in its first week, according to Netflix. It is inarguably popular, and the point of this Weekly Top 10 is not merely to recommend the best shows on streaming, but to also tell you which shows are getting the most attention, regardless of their critical reception. Dahmer is getting a ton of buzz. Its mostly bad, even gross buzzbut its buzz nonetheless. Andrew Gruttadaro

Smile was a massive box-office hit in 2022: Writer-director Parker Finns debut grossed more than $200 million worldwide during a monstrous theatrical run. Its also one of the creepiest movies of the year: Sosie Bacon plays Dr. Rose Cotter, a psychiatrist who, after witnessing a traumatic, inexplicable incident with a patient, begins to experience horrifying supernatural occurrences of her own. Smile has everything from captivating mystery and nightmare-inducing jump scares to a bewildering final twist. And now, its available on Paramount+. Stream at your own risk. Kai Grady
shows.title: Smile

shows.writeup: Fleishman Is in Troubles themes are largely internal, its plot often passive. The inciting incident of its story is an absence, a Rachel-sized hole Toby and Libby fill with probing questions: Who controls a relationships narrative after its end? What are the compromises and conflicts inherent in long-term partnership, and what flaws prove truly fatal? Why is Libby, and why are we, so quick to take Tobys side? Which Fleishman, once we have all the facts, is truly in trouble? Alison Herman
shows.title: Fleishman Is in Trouble
Captain America: Civil War
shows.writeup: The third Captain America film might as well be an Avengers movie: The whole gangs here as the world reacts to the decimation of Sokovia and its people that occurred in Avengers: Age of Ultron. After the UN demands to oversee and regulate the superhero squad, the team is divided into two camps: those who think regulation is necessary and those who refuse oversight. Civil War stands as the MCUs official initiation of Chadwick Bosemans Black Panther. Hes a main cog in Civil War, and the movie sets up his stand-alone film while also bringing established characters like Bucky Barnes to his homeland of Wakanda.

The basics sound normal enough: a reboot of the Addams family focusing on its sardonic adolescent daughter, shepherded by Tim Burton and starring the rising scream queen Jenna Ortega (Scream, X). But the results are anything but normal: Wednesday comes off like a streaming sibling to Riverdale, the series from the CW that practically perfected the so-bonkers-its-great model. There are dance numbers, theres a stellar performance from a hand, and oh boy, there are memes. Its the perfect show for wasting time, and a lot of people wasted time when it came out over Thanksgiving weekend. Wednesday wont reconfigure your idea of what television can be, but itll certainly make sure you dont forget it. Andrew Gruttadaro
shows.title: Wednesday

shows.writeup: God bless the person at Talkback who dared to ask the question: What happens when you put a group of hot, horny people together and forbid them from engaging in sexual activity for the chance to earn cold, hard cash? Its a silly premise, but Too Hot to Handle pulls off a keen balancing act of not taking itself too seriously while also creating an environment where its f-boy and f-girl contestants can learn from their past behavior and grow. Whether or not said contestants, who are as horny for fame as they are for each other, listen and actually absorb the information is for the viewer to discern. Amelia Wedemeyer
shows.title: Too Hot to Handle

shows.writeup: The Makanai is the first TV series from Hirokazu Kore-eda, the Palme d'Orwinning director of Shoplifters and, most recently, Broker. But this Netflix series isn't the expensive, self-serious drama you'd typically expect from an A-list filmmaker pivoting to the small screen. Based on a popular manga, The Makanai is the sweet, low-key story of two childhood best friends who travel to Kyoto to enroll as maiko, apprentices who will one day become geiko, or geishas. But one of the girls, Kiyo, discovers her culinary skills when filling in for the house chefhence the subtitle. A gentle coming-of-age story augmented by lots of mouthwatering close-ups, The Makanai makes for a lovely, immersive binge. Alison Herman
shows.title: The Makanai: Cooking for the Maiko House

shows.writeup: Its Harrison Ford and Helen Mirren in a Yellowstone prequelIm not sure I need to say anything more. And while sure, Taylor Sheridans numerical universe may be expanding at a rapid rate because Paramount doesnt own the streaming rights to Yellowstone proper and needs shows to put on its own service, in this case whos complaining? Ford stars as Jake Dutton and Mirren as his wife, Cara, two feisty pioneers who started the tradition of Dutton family members going to war with every human who steps foot on their land. Also? One of the Duttons is big-game hunting in Africa, for some reason. Whatever. Dont ask questions. Questions just get in the way. Andrew Gruttadaro

shows.title: Mike
shows.writeup: Mike Tyson would prefer you not watch Mike, the unauthorized limited seriesemphasis on the unauthorizedairing on Hulu. Created by Steven Rogers of I, Tonya, the show takes a similarly irreverent approach to its controversial subject, starring Moonlights Trevante Rhodes in a bald cap and face tattoos. Speaking in Tysons signature lisp, Rhodes breaks the fourth wall to tell his characters life story, from a rough childhood in Brooklyn to championships to tabloids. Tyson himself claims the show stole his life story, but its portrait is a surprisingly flattering one, with more tongue-in-cheek humor than soul-searching drama. Alison Herman
The fall of the Jedi and the Empire's victory sets the stage for the Rebel Alliance and the evolution of the "good guys" in the Republic.
shows.title: Star Wars: Episode III  Revenge of the Sith

shows.writeup: After beginning his career in the era of word-of-mouth rollouts, Stanley Kubrick released his first mass-market movie: The Shining. Unveiled over Memorial Day weekend by Warner Bros., the film was supposed to be a landmark: an apex in the blockbusterization of the Hollywood horror movie. This trajectory was kick-started in 1968 by the A-list credits of Rosemarys Baby, put together by producer Robert Evans as a designer package pairing a hot young European director (Roman Polanski), a glamorous ingenue (Mia Farrow), and an independent-film hero (John Cassavetes). It was consolidated in 1973 by The Exorcist, a holiday-season release whose R ratingas opposed to the dreaded X it seemingly warrantedmeant that it could provide two hours of Christmas Day entertainment for the whole family.  In theory, The Shinings marriage of pulp and pedigree, mounted on a generous $19 million budget (almost 10 times the cost of Brian De Palmas Carrie) was unprecedented. Stephen Kings source novel was a bestseller to rival The Exorcist, building upon the schlockier shocks of Carrie and Salems Lot to establish its author as a pop-literary titanone formidable enough that Kubrick, whose previous cinematic adaptations had been of canon-caliber writers from Vladimir Nabokov to William Makepeace Thackeray, thought his haunted-house saga was worthy of working with. Adam Nayman
shows.title: The Shining

shows.writeup: For better or worse, being a sinister emcee is the most notable contribution Guillermo del Toro makes to the series that bears his name. While del Toro originally planned to helm an episode, pandemic-induced production delays on Nightmare Alley and his Pinocchio remake required him to step away from a more active role. (Of the eight installments, two are based on original stories from del Toro, who also cowrote one of the teleplays.) But with del Toros absence behind the camera, Cabinet of Curiosities instead relies on a murderers row of exciting filmmakers who have made their mark in horror, including Jennifer Kent (The Babadook), David Prior (The Empty Man), Ana Lily Amirpour (A Girl Walks Home Alone at Night), and Panos Cosmatos (Mandy). As a result, Cabinet of Curiosities is best appreciated as a showcase for how the genre can house such an intriguing range of tones and ideas. Miles Surrey
shows.title: Guillermo del Toros Cabinet of Curiosities
Kindred
shows.writeup: Kindred centers on Dana (Mallori Johnson), a writer in Los Angeles who finds herself transported to a Maryland plantation in 1815. Over a few traumatic visits, Dana starts to understand whats drawn her back in time: Rufus Weylin (David Alexander Kaplan), a young boy whose parents, Thomas (Ryan Kwanten) and Margaret (Gayle Rankin), own the plantation. Whenever Dana is yanked back in time, she finds Rufus in mortal danger, reeling from an accident or suffering from illness. Slowly, she begins to grasp what ties her and Rufus together. Like many Black Americans, Dana is descended from both slavers and the enslaved. When he grows up, Rufus will enforce a system that brutalizes and controls people like Dana. He will also become her ancestor. Alison Herman

After a half-decade of anticipationand much discussion about per-episode budgetsAmazons Lord of the Rings prequel series, The Rings of Power, will debut its first two episodes on September 2. But first, its worth going back (while technically going forward). The time to study up on J.R.R. Tolkiens fascinating and vast world is nowof course, it doesnt hurt that the homework is rewatching the most epic trilogy of the 21st century. Reunite with Frodo, Aragorn, and Gollum and then find out whether The Rings of Power is worthy of their company. Andrew Gruttadaro
shows.title: The Lord of the Rings Trilogy

shows.writeup: If You Can Watch Only One Season: Indulge in Season 3 for an all-star roster of housewives that includes NeNe Leakes, Kim Zolciak-Biermann, Kandi Burruss, Shere Whitfield, Cynthia Bailey, and Phaedra Parks.
shows.title: The Real Housewives of Atlanta
The White Lotus
shows.writeup: To establish itself as a separate story, this new White Lotus infuses a fresh set of themes. Mike White has billed these seven episodes, five of which were shared with critics in advance as a bedroom farce with teeth. On this particular holiday, jealousy, lust, and longing are as much a currency as the Euro. Theyre what drive Tanya (Jennifer Coolidge) to keep clinging to her now-husband Greg (Jon Gries), though his early attraction has long since curdled into exasperated resentment. Theyre what lead Harper (Aubrey Plaza) and Ethan (Will Sharpe)newly rich after the sale of Ethans startupto obsessively evaluate Daphne (Meghann Fahy) and Cam (Theo James), the old-money acquaintances who invited them on a couples trip. Theyre what unite three generations of Di Grasso men, in Italy to tour their ancestral home: Bert (F. Murray Abraham), an aging horndog; Dom (Michael Imperioli), a self-loathing lothario; and Albie (Adam DiMarco), a sensitive Stanford grad who wants to be a better manor at least not an actively awful one. The simplest spin on Season 2 is that The White Lotus has traded the class war for a battle of the sexes, but such a summary would miss the point. White knows that sex, like money, is a form of power, and that each is intimately bound up in the other. Alison Herman
If You Can Watch Only One Season: Give Season 6set in Las Vegasa try for its addition of the high-stakes quickfire mini challenges.
shows.title: Top Chef
Below Deck
shows.writeup: If You Can Watch Only One Season: Try the shows sixth season for boat romances, lush views of Tahiti, and a deckhands near-death experience.

The first season of Survivor, later renamed Survivor: Borneo, kicked off the reality boom of the 2000s and ushered in a genre that has lifted many of its stars to mythic proportions. That being said, whats great about the cast of Survivor: Borneo is that it really feels like people plucked from everyday lifepeople you might know or encounter on a daily basis, a quality that Survivor has mostly managed to maintain in a way that other reality shows have not. Season 1 is also a great place to start because of its Survivor firsts: first villain, first alliance, first showmance, first Jeff Probst speechthe list goes on. (Also streaming on Hulu.)
shows.title: Survivor: Borneo
The Fabelmans
shows.writeup:
The ghost of John Ford has always hovered over Steven Spielbergs films, and his burnished autobiographical fantasia The Fabelmans gives the man they called Pappy his close-up, coming in like the cavalry in the final scene to dispense crucial filmmaking advice to his spiritual protg. But if Fords great theme was the relationship of outsiders to their communitythe conceptual lynchpin of the American WesternThe Fabelmans manifests it in fascinating ways, positing young Sammy F. (whose home frontier is scenic Phoenix) as a misfit whose gift for heightening life through the camera lens tempts him equally toward heroism and villainy. No wonder the most important movie in this exquisitely executed ode to the medium is Fords The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance, a majestic meditation on who gets to write history and why. The question is less whether Spielberg has earned the right to print his own legend than whats at stake when the greatest escapist filmmaker of all time gets confessionalwhether hes betraying his gift or, more powerfully, examining and illuminating it once and for all. Adam Nayman

Streaming now on VOD.

shows.title: Nailed It!
shows.writeup: On the other end of the amatuer baking spectrum is Nailed It!, which features hilariously incompetent chefs trying to recreate intricate dishes. Appetizing? No. Entertaining? Absolutely.

shows.title: The Watcher
shows.writeup: The camp lunacy of American Horror Story lives on in The Watcher, which essentially reruns the plot of American Horror Story: Murder House with antique dumbwaiters in lieu of leather gimp suits. Back in 2011, that first seasonthen simply billed as American Horror Story; the subtitle is retroactiveshocked fans by killing off most of its cast, then changed the course of television by reinventing itself as an anthology. (You can date a decades worth of prestige miniseries, movie star migration, and award gamesmanship back to that one clever twist.) In 2022, The Watcher doesnt have the element of surprise on its side, at least in terms of a structural bait-and-switch. Instead, its content to embellish the details of the New York magazine article its based on, turning a realist sketch of NIMBY paranoia into a supernatural romp. Alison Herman

page.intro:
The story of music in 1999 is, in retrospect, two stories. On the one hand, MTVs 90s ascendance—a rise accelerated at the end of the decade by Total Request Live—precipitated the return of the single (and its accompanying music video) as the most important commercial product an artist could release. Artists best-equipped to market their sound with compelling visuals reached newfound levels of fame: the maximalist boy bands NSync and the Backstreet Boys, Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, TLC, and rappers with enticing narratives and crossover potential like Jay-Z. And also some weirder phenomena: Lou Begas mambo revival, Eiffel 65s all-blue-everything. TRL, and pop music in general, was a marketing machine—and the artists who were most marketable thrived. 

At the same time, albums were still important—Napster had not yet delivered the death blow—and for more invested listeners, an important explosion and collision of genres was underway. Hip-hop was further and further expanding its market share in the mainstream; the grunge of the early 90s had given way to a more accessible version dubbed pop-punk; emo was on the rise; indie music was having a renaissance; and bands like Rage Against the Machine, the Roots, and Nine Inch Nails were blurring the lines between genres. 

Which is why, for The Ringers retrospective ranking of music in 1999, we decided to separate the singles from the albums—to fully encapsulate the depth, range, and utter weirdness of music 20 years ago. One other programming note: Only albums released in 1999 were eligible, while singles released in 1999 and ones that didnt peak on the Billboard Hot 100 until 1999 were eligible. It only felt right to be able to recognize this guy and this guy at the same time. 

Now, turn on Millennium—or, I guess, Willennium—and dive into one of the most interesting years of music ever.

streaming_wars.content:
For a few years, it was all pretty simple: Netflix ran the show, Hulu had sneaky value, and Prime Video had Fleabag. But when the calendar changed from October to November in 2019, so too did the entire streaming industry. Apple TV+ launched on the first of the month, flanked by stars like Reese Witherspoon, Jennifer Aniston, Steve Carell, and Jason Momoa; 11 days later, Disney+ put its stake in the ground with an instant phenomenon. (Two words: Baby Yoda.) Others would join over the following months: HBO Max in May 2020, NBCUniversals Peacock in July, and later Paramount+, a rebrand of CBS All Access. (And also Quibi; let us not forget the quick bites.) What was already a hard-to-navigate landscape2019 offered 532 original scripted serieshad become impossibly flooded, as the biggest corporations in the entertainment (and tech!) businesses clamored for a piece of the streaming pie.

Almost two years later, things have calmed down. Just kiddingthe Streaming Wars are more chaotic than theyve ever been. Netflix is finally starting to show some cracks, HBO Max wont even be called HBO Max 12 months from now, and Prime Video is on the verge of dropping the most expensive show in television history. As the competitive pool gets crowded and Netflixs massive head start gets erased, the fight for streaming preeminence grows more and more heated. 

That makes for pretty fun scoreboard-watchingand pretty complicated TV watching. Which is why were introducing this section to not only keep tabs on the ever-changing Streaming Wars, but also to explain how those developments translate to you, the person whos doing the streaming. Every week, well use a proprietary formula to determine how the biggest players in the Streaming Wars stack up against each otherand more importantly, which ones are worth your hard-earned cash. When Netflix has a record-breaking hit on its hands, well explain how that helps its standing in the larger race; when HBO Max has an earnings call that makes the internet ask existential questions about the future of all media, thatll be reflected here, as well. The Ringers Streaming Wars formula takes five different factors into account:

  • A streaming services quality of TV content (and not just original content)
  • A services buzz or hype (Did it have a good week?)
  • A services level of prestige (Does it win awards?)
  • A services utility as an app (Does it make TV watching better?)
  • The average cost of a service

Plugging these metrics into our formulawhile giving particular weight to quality of content and buzzproduces a Streaming Wars score. The services with higher Streaming Wars scores are not only prevailing at the moment, but are also the ones most worth paying for. Knowing which streaming services are on top can feel downright impossible. And things are only going to get messier. Hopefully this guide can make it a little easier, and bring you back to the days when watching TV was so much simpler.
